hands_on_practices.problem:
Let the sequence of sets $\{C_n\}_{n=0}^{\infty}$ be defined by the standard construction of the Cantor ternary set. We start with $C_0 = [0, 1]$. For each $n \ge 1$, the set $C_n$ is obtained from $C_{n-1}$ by removing the open middle third of each disjoint closed interval that constitutes $C_{n-1}$. For example, $C_1 = [0, 1/3] \cup [2/3, 1]$.

Now, consider a new sequence of sets $\{A_n\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$, defined within the universe $[0, 1]$. For any positive integer $n$, the set $A_n$ is defined as follows:
$$
A_n = \begin{cases}
C_n  \text{if } n \text{ is odd} \\
[0, 1] \setminus C_n  \text{if } n \text{ is even}
\end{cases}
$$
Determine the limit superior of the sequence $\{A_n\}$, denoted as $\limsup_{n \to \infty} A_n$. Express your answer using standard interval notation.
